text: When I think about what are the traits or the qualities we look for in the research team, I mean, there's a few things that are important. So I think it goes without saying that you want high intelligence and a good quantitative background. Those are essentially table stakes for what we do. But we're not looking for a particular pedigree or a particular degree. I mean, we found that the skill set we need in terms of math, stats, programming are found across a range of STEM fields. And so it's not so much what field you have your degree in. And we do like the diversity of perspectives that comes from a lot of different academic backgrounds. But the soft skills are also pretty important. I think we're looking for curiosity. The ability to generate original ideas is very important. We want to make sure that team members are resilient because the research process is hard. You run into a lot of obstacles and you want to make sure people are going to be able to overcome that. We're looking for researchers that are skeptical, that don't take ideas at face value. Collaborative mindset obviously is important. And finally, we want people that are results oriented. We do have people with strong academic background. We want people that have a strong background, but we don't want an ivory tower mindset. We want people that are excited about seeing their ideas make an impact on the portfolio. The other thing I'll say is that our team has really been built in-house from the ground up. We don't bolt on teams. At least we've not found the opportunity to do that. And again, I think in terms of that collaborative culture and cohesion of the culture, that's been an important piece for us.
